The food menu itself is extensive and you order your selections via iPad which includes photos. This was awesome as some of the items I wasn't as familiar with. The restaurant itself is small/medium size but since the tables are so big to fit the hot pot, there can be limited seating during the busy dinner rush. New York, NY 10019

Soupe Du Jour
Quiche Du Jour
Grand Marnier Cr√®me Br√ªl√©e
Goat Cheese Salad
Petites Soupieres de la Mer
Dame Blanche

There is no need to wait around for restaurant week because this specialty French restaurant serves prix fixe meals all year round.

Choose  a 2-course lunch prix fixe or a 3-course dinner prix fixe for a set price.

Soupe Du Jour:
The smooth tomato soup was hot and creamy.  The best part was dipping the toasted baguette, which was a perfect replacement for the typical croutons.  It was undoubtedly one of the best appetizers especially during the colder months of the year.

Quiche Du Jour:
This thick, crusty French tart was packed with spinach.  It also came with a refreshing side salad.

Grand Marnier Cr√®me Br√ªl√©e:
For small upcharge, I added a third course to the lunch prix fixe.  Usually three‚Äôs a crowd, but that certainly is not the case here.  The custard was very tasty and was topped with a hardened caramel shell.

Goat Cheese Salad:
This gourmet salad was piled high and deep with mixed greens and fruit.  The goat cheese was the backbone to this starter.

Petites Soupieres de la Mer:
If you are looking for an upscale seafood version of a pot pie, you‚Äôve found it!  This entr√©e is loaded with mussels, scallops, clams and an assortment of vegetables.

Dame Blanche:
Watch and observe as le serveur pours hot chocolate syrup over this  phenomenal closer to the meal.

The inside is filled with a heaping pile of chantilly cream and lightly sprinkled with almonds.

Stop by if you want to try top quality French cuisine.  The prix fixe is definitely the best pick.

Most importantly, the pacing was just right‚Äîwe never felt rushed, which made the whole experience even more enjoyable. It‚Äôs a great spot for a casual date night or a relaxed catch-up with friends.

As a bagel lover, I was impressed to see their reimagined Smoked Salmon with Everything Bagel into yubu!

The Hiramasa was an indulgent bite, generously crowned with caviar for that extra touch of luxury.

My friend couldn‚Äôt stop raving about the Scallop, finished with a drizzle of brown butter dashi.

Moving forward to some special and unexpected toppings: The Duck Pastrami was a standout with its smoky and peppery taste. The sweet Korean Beef Tartare reminded me of bulgogi. While the Pork Belly with Mushroom Pickle, served with a piece of lettuce, felt like a playful nod to kbbq.

But what really caught us off guard in the best way were the desserts. The Earl Grey Soft Serve sprinkled with sea salt might just be the BEST dessert I‚Äôve ever had, and the portion was generous. It was rich with tea flavor even by my standard, subtly savory.

There‚Äôs something deliciously smug about finding a great meal in a place that doesn‚Äôt try too hard. Tucked inside Olly Olly Market ‚ÄìManhattan‚Äôs answer to the question ‚Äúwhat if a food court grew up, got a better job, and started dressing well?‚Äù ‚Äì you‚Äôll find DDOBAR, quietly turning out food that deserves its own parade.

I visited with a dear South Korean friend, a man who knows his way around both a tasting menu and a street cart, and whose standards make Michelin judges look forgiving. We both left beaming ‚Äî the rare kind of culinary happiness where you start planning your next visit before you‚Äôve even paid the bill.

The scallop dish is where the kitchen makes its intentions clear: seared to the whisper of golden brown, barely cooked through, and still carrying the clean, briny sweetness of the ocean. It doesn‚Äôt come with a novel-sized explanation. It doesn‚Äôt need to.

Then came the shrimp on fried tofu, affectionately called ‚Äúyubutart,‚Äù and here, DDOBAR truly shows its swagger. The tofu is crisp without, silken within. The shrimp sweet, juicy, and sauced with enough punch to wake you up but not so much as to drown the thing‚Äôs natural beauty. It‚Äôs clever without being show-offy ‚Äì the culinary version of someone who‚Äôs extremely good-looking but also knows how to tell a joke.

Olly Olly Market itself buzzes with energy: a sleek, Manhattan-polished take on the classic food hall, where every stand feels like a secret you‚Äôre lucky to have overheard. It‚Äôs the kind of place where you realize why New York ruins other cities for you.

If you‚Äôre smart, you‚Äôll find your way to DDOBAR. If you‚Äôre lucky, you‚Äôll bring a friend who gets it. Either way, expect to leave feeling slightly smug ‚Äî and already plotting a return.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'A Hidden Gem in Manhattan‚Äôs Coolest Food Court

Food 10/10
I am a fan of everything Noz. We All Gotta Eat Group does it again with this superb omakase experience. It‚Äôs a little more experimental, and more varied in piece selection, but a stellar meal nonetheless. Excellent quality of fish of course, but had a greater number of unique dishes and ingredients. Felt like there were fewer nigiri compared to Sushi Noz. I love the way Chef Matsuzaki plays with different textures and combinations of ingredients.

I am actually obsessed with the rice. It was warmer than other omakases I‚Äôve been to, and the rice itself was seasoned with the perfect amount of vinegar, slightly sweet, and a perfect complement to the fish. The rice size itself was also not too big, so I was able to eat all 23 pieces. Again, 23 pieces is insane and such a great way to explore the diverse ingredients. I could eat omakase every day for the rest of my life.

Omakase list:
Japanese winter potato
Chutoro: aged one week
Yellowtail
Stewed octopus
Baby sea bream
Steamed egg and male snow crab
Baby bluefin tuna
Monkfish liver, shirako, caviar: a massive piece I attempted to stuff all in my mouth, and it melted immediately

Cuttlefish

Scallop on scallop
Whitefish
Gizzard fish with shrimp flakes
Clam:
Black codfish: seared and topped with homemade sauce
Lean bluefin tuna
Otoro: love

Chestnut paste dessert

It's BYOB so they don't serve alcoholic beverages. However, there is a liquor store right next door.

Each dish was unique and had its own robust flavor profile. We ordered quite a few items, and there was something that each of us enjoyed most. Each dish reviewed below:

Peking Duck - I personally loved the Peking Duck the most. It was just as everyone else described- juicy, crunchy, flavorful. Will definitely be coming back for this.

Stir fried cabbage with pork belly - Another highlight. This was such a pleasant surprise as it was soooo flavorful and complex.

Deep fried chicken with dough and dried pepper- This dish was very good however I expected it to be much more spicy. It definitely has a kick, but I was hoping for more.

Hand peeled crab meat- this was the favorite dish of my dining partner. I also enjoyed it, but preferred other dishes over this one.

Kimchi cheese fried rice - This was the first time trying this dish, my dining partner again really enjoyed this, but it wasn't my favorite.

Stewed egg with truffle - a nice start to the dinner. The truffle flavor is great but the dish lacked a bit of salt which would have made everything come together much more cohesively.

[{'name': 'places/ChIJiag-Wq5ZwokR9x2Wlf7j7dc/reviews/ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJejNfSS1jdDhMQlJ3EAE', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': 'in the last week', 'rating': 5, 'text': {'text': "short: best customer service of any Krispy Kreme in Manhattan, from Jeremiah & Harouma (sp?)

long: placed an online order for a dozen to take to the office to share with coworkers. I was curious on why there was no official Little Cuba in NYC. After my trip to Miami 2 weekends ago, I was looking for fresh Cuban food and, to my surprise, I found out that right across the water in Bergen, NJ, there was a massive Cuban community.

For 2 miles on Bergenline Street, starting from Jose Marti Field all the way up to Racetrack Section, lies dozens upon dozens of Cuban eateries and bakeries

Just like every country has their own style of Pizza, La Burana specializes in Cuban style Pizza and Speghetti. The pizza was distinct enough to stand out as it‚Äôs own genre. What makes the pizza here different than American style is that the toppings are mixed into the pizza while cooking instead of just being sprayed on top

There are only 2 specialized Cuban Pizza spots, with this one being the newer and smaller in the neighborhood

The owners are recent immigrants from Havana and their honor of authenticity was enough to make me order a king‚Äôs worth of food

This place was probably the most affordable place I‚Äôve been to: $6 for entire customized pan pizzes, $5 for a massive plate of speghetti, and $1 fresh scoops of ice cream. My total bill came iut to $20 and that was enough to feed me for 3-4 full meals

- Eating my way through offbeat immigrant-owned small mom-and-pop shops in NYC

reviews:
[{'name': 'places/ChIJpY9Tg01YwokRCr_aQpDrqgk/reviews/ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTURvNDRpSjVRRRAB', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': '2 weeks ago', 'rating': 3, 'text': {'text': '6-day stay at this hotel:
Comfortable and pleasant hotel ‚Äî unless you are staying on the 4th floor. If so, I recommend asking for a room change.

Very noisy hotel:
We stayed on the 4th floor, where the reception, restaurant, and cabaret are also located.
Between 6:00 PM and 9:30 PM, we could clearly hear the music and applause from the cabaret.
The proximity of the gym also added noise (treadmills running, weights dropping), and the walls are too thin to properly block the sounds.
Rooms on higher floors (5th to 27th) would likely be much quieter.

Otherwise:
The hotel is stylish and pleasant. The rooms are small but cozy, with a slightly "futuristic" design.
